<table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>But even &ldquo;good&rdquo; metaphors don&rsquo;t always work. For instance, in an informal survey of <a href="guis/macos">Macintosh</a>-literate university students, many people failed to employ the word &ldquo;desktop&rdquo; anywhere in their description of the Finder.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/macos'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Mac OS' alt='Mac OS' src='intr/osicons/macos.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Brenda Laurel, &ldquo;Computers as theatre,&rdquo; p. 5, 1993)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>But there are two ways to fall off the desktop. One is when you start looking for the other things that &ldquo;go&rdquo; with it and you can&rsquo;t find them &ndash; filing cabinets, telephones, blotters for doodling and making notes or even an administrative assistant to make some calls or type some letters. The other way to fall of the desktop is to find something on it that doesn&rsquo;t go with everything else &ndash; for example, a trash can that gobbles up your trash seemingly at random and eject your disks.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Brenda Laurel, &ldquo;Computers as theatre,&rdquo; p. 131, 1990)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b><a href="guis/geos/geoworks">GeoWorks Ensemble</a> is a little-known but worthy competitor for <a href="guis/windows">Windows</a>. GeoWorks is a good value. It can bring easier, more productive computing to desktops where Windows strikes out.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/geos'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='GEOS/GeoWorks' alt='GEOS/GeoWorks' src='intr/osicons/geos.png'></a><a href='guis/windows'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Windows' alt='Windows' src='intr/osicons/windows.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Walt Mossberg, The Wall Street Journal, October 24, 1991)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>Here&rsquo;s today&rsquo;s true confession: I like Bob. No, I don&rsquo;t mean Bob Dole or Bob Dylan. I mean <a href="guis/bob">Microsoft Bob</a>, the radical new $99 software program designed to replace the sometimes confusing menus and icons of Microsoft&rsquo;s <a href="guis/windows">Windows</a>.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/bob'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Bob' alt='Bob' src='intr/osicons/bob.png'></a><a href='guis/windows'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Windows' alt='Windows' src='intr/osicons/windows.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Walt Mossberg, The Wall Street Journal, March 30, 1995)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>My favorite <a href="guis/macos">Macintosh</a> example is an error message that I sometimes encounter while running Multifinder: &ldquo;Excel (or some other application) has unexpectedly quit.&rdquo; &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; I usually reply, &ldquo;the capricious little bastard!&rdquo;<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/macos'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Mac OS' alt='Mac OS' src='intr/osicons/macos.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Brenda Laurel, &ldquo;Computers as theatre,&rdquo; p. 63, 1993)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b><a href="guis/newton">Newton</a> has set the whole category of PDAs back by two years.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/newton'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Newton OS' alt='Newton OS' src='intr/osicons/newton.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Bill Gates, Microsoft&rsquo;s CEO)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>No. It&rsquo;s no evolution at all. It&rsquo;s no advance at all. [The users are still] stuck in this morass of overlapping windows.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/macos'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Mac OS' alt='Mac OS' src='intr/osicons/macos.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Jef Raskin on <a href="guis/macos/macosx">Mac OS X</a>)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>Steve [Jobs] had an incredible ability to rally people towards some common cause by painting an incredibly glorious cosmic objective. One of his favorite statements about <a href="guis/lisa">the Lisa</a> was, &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s make a dent in the universe. We&rsquo;ll make it so important that it will make a dent in the universe.&rdquo;<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Trip Hawkins, manager of marketing planning for Lisa)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b><a href="guis/lisa">The Lisa</a> failed because it was very underpowered, and so, while it did beautiful things, it did them very slowly.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Alan Kay)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>The <a href="guis/nextstep">NeXT</a> interface was beautiful, smooth, and consistent. It had great flexibility, and other features that would not be seen on PCs till later, such as voice e-mail, and a built-in synthesizer. it also had software to create a hypertext program. Its failure to take over the industry, despite all these advantages, became for me a cautionary tale. NeXT required users to accept all these innovations at once &ndash; too much.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/nextstep'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='NeXTSTEP/OPENSTEP/Rhapsody' alt='NeXTSTEP/OPENSTEP/Rhapsody' src='intr/osicons/nextstep.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Tim Berners-Lee, &ldquo;Weaving the web,&rdquo; p. 28, 1999)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>The <a href="guis/nextstep">NeXT</a> machine&rsquo;s &ldquo;black hole&rdquo; icon is an interesting alternative [to <a href="guis/macos">Macintosh</a>&rsquo;s trash can], but <i>as a metaphor</i> it suggests a disturbing irreversibility. One can, after all, take things back out of a trash can &ndash; usually.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/macos'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Mac OS' alt='Mac OS' src='intr/osicons/macos.png'></a><a href='guis/nextstep'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='NeXTSTEP/OPENSTEP/Rhapsody' alt='NeXTSTEP/OPENSTEP/Rhapsody' src='intr/osicons/nextstep.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Brenda Laurel, &ldquo;Computers as theatre,&rdquo; p. 131, 1993)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>The mouse is quite sturdy and can tolerate a lot of rolling and button-pressing. However, a sudden impact could damage the sensors inside. Avoid dropping the mouse or hitting it against hard objects.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (from <a href="guis/lisa">Lisa</a> Owner&rsquo;s Guide)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>There is also a little arrow on the screen which points NNE. This is the mouse-pointer.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Richard King, <a href="articles/appleslisa">Apple&rsquo;s Lisa</a>)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>We are told to believe that this is a &ldquo;metaphor&rdquo; for a &ldquo;desktop.&rdquo; But I have never personally seen a desktop where pointing at a lower piece of paper makes it jump to the top, or where placing a sheet of paper on top of a file folder caused the folder to gobble it up; I do not believe such desks exist; and I do not think I would want one if it did.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Theodor H. Nelson, &ldquo;The right way to think about software design,&rdquo; 1990) </td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>We want to drive this industry. We could have introduced <a href="guis/lisa">Lisa</a> a year ago, but we wanted to make it perfect. We&rsquo;re prepared to live with Lisa for the next ten years.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Steve Jobs, Time magazine, January 1983)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>Whatever Apple&rsquo;s plans are, we think it extremely unlikely that it would introduce a similar product that would undercut their <a href="guis/lisa">Lisa</a> system so soon after its costly development and introduction. Indeed, we cannot see the benefit that would be gained by such action. So, whatever MacIntosh [sic] may turn out to be and whenever it finally appears, we think it is more likely that it will be clearly differentiated from the Lisa offering.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a><a href='guis/macos'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Mac OS' alt='Mac OS' src='intr/osicons/macos.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Joseph L. Ehardt, The Seybold Report on Professional Computing, January 1983)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>When the mouse is moved on the surface of a desk, an arrow moves on <a href="guis/lisa">Lisa</a>&rsquo;s TV-like monitor screen. This permits the user to juggle words or statistics around in much the same way that a child uses a joystick to manipulate spaceships in a video game.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Peter Nulty, <a href="articles/applesbidtostayinthebigtime">Apple&rsquo;s bid to stay in the big time</a>)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br><table class=reg width=100%><tr><td width=85%><b>&ldquo;</b>[<a href="guis/lisa">Lisa</a>] turns the tedious chore of drafting office reports into something close to playing a video game.<b>&rdquo;</b></td><td width=15% align=right valign=top><a href='guis/lisa'><img align=right width=32 height=32 border=0 title='Lisa Office System' alt='Lisa Office System' src='intr/osicons/lisa.png'></a></td></tr><tr><td colspan=2 align=right> (Peter Nulty, <a href="articles/applesbidtostayinthebigtime">Apple&rsquo;s bid to stay in the big time</a>)</td></tr></table><br clear=all><br><br></td><td height=50 style='background: url(intr/3rightfill.png)'><img width=12 height=1 src='intr/3rightfill.png'></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td height=30><img width=50 height=30 hspace=0 src='intr/31bottomleft.png'></td><td height=30 width=100% style='background: url(intr/31bottomfill.png)'></td><td height=30><img width=47 height=30 hspace=0 src='intr/31bottomclosed.png'></td></tr></table></td></tr></table><table width=100% cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td valign=top width=50 style='background: url(intr/1leftfill.png) top left repeat-y'><img width=50 src='intr/1leftfill.png'></td><td width=100% class=box1text>
